>[Question]
>A store has a raffle based on New York's lottery pick 3 for the 
month 
>of October.  The store sells 1000 tickets (000-999).  If one was to 
>buy 100 tickets, would his odds be better buying 100 random tickets 
>or a block of 100 tickets (for example 200-299). I thought one's 
odds 
>would be greatly increased if one bought a block of tickets (200-
299)
>b/c your odds are only based on the first number to come up.  One 
has 
>a 1 in 10 chance of a 2 coming up.  If a 2 came up you won b/c you 
>have every possible sequence that may result with the other two 
>numbers as a result of having tickets 200-299.  My co-workers 
believe 
>the odds are the same, b/c either way you still have 100 tickets or 
>10% of the population.  My agruement was by having a block of 
tickets 
>(200-299) you elimante the chances of not having the second and 
third 
>number.  One's odds of winning are 1 in 10, whereas if have a 
random 
>tickets you have a 1 in 1000 of winning.  I appreciate you taking 
the 
>time to assist us in resolving this problem.
>
>Thank you
>
>[Difficulty]
>My co-workers and I have been out of school for 10 years and we do 
>taxes for a living.
>
>[Thoughts]
>

The probability is 1/10 whether you buy a block of 10 tickets or 10 
tickets chosen randomly over the whole range.


